  "response": "If Donald Trump were to die during the election process, the Republican Party would have a process to replace him as their presidential nominee. Typically, the Republican National Committee (RNC) would convene and select a new candidate, likely someone from party leadership or a prominent Republican figure. The specific replacement would depend on the timing and circumstances. If it happened very close to the election, it could create significant political uncertainty and potentially impact voter preferences. The new nominee would need to quickly organize a campaign and gain party and voter support. The exact process is governed by party rules and electoral laws, which can vary somewhat by state.",
